  <body>

    <h1>Test CC Guidelines</h1>

    <h3>Description</h3>
    <div>
      This is the simplest working setup to get links to pages like
      <ul>
        <li>
          <a target="_new" href="http://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/mark/1.0/">http://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/mark/1.0/</a>
        </li>
      </ul>
      linking back to data in the referring document. (jump to <a href="#test-link">test link</a>)

    </div>

    <h3>The Data Needed</h3>
    <h4>namespaces</h4>
    <div>
        No metadata is needed in the head of the document, but somewhere there has to be an element -
        <span class=highlight
         xmlns:cc="http://creativecommons.org/ns#"
         xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/"
         xmlns:xhv="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml/vocab#">like this span</span>
        - that has the xml namespace attributes:
       <ul>
         <li>xmlns:cc="http://creativecommons.org/ns#"</li>
         <li>xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/"</li>
         <li>xmlns:xhv="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml/vocab#"</li>
       </ul>
    </div>

    <h4>title</h4>
    <div>
      The "Work Details" title label comes from this span: <span class=highlight property="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/title dc:title">Test Title</span>
      which has the attribute
      <ul>
        <li>property="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/title dc:title"</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <h4>attribution</h4>
    <div>
      It is the link to
       <a property="cc:attributionName"
          rel="cc:attributionURL"
          href="http://www.bl.uk/catalogues/illuminatedmanuscripts/ILLUMIN.ASP?Size=mid&IllID=22963">
          the work's origin
       </a>
      that generates the content of the "cite" box.  These attributes are necessary:
      <ul>
        <li>property="cc:attributionName"</li>
        <li>rel="cc:attributionURL"</li>
        <li>href="the edm isShownAt"</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <h4>a guidelines referencing element</h4>
    <div>
      We have an element - like
      <span rel="cc:useGuidelines" resource="http://www.europeana.eu/rights/pd-usage-guide/">this span</span> -
      with attributes referencing the guidelines document:
      <ul>
        <li>rel="cc:useGuidelines"</li>
        <li>resource="http://www.europeana.eu/rights/pd-usage-guide/"</li>
      </ul>
      This becomes the href of the "<span class=highlight>Non-binding use guidelines apply to this work</span>" text
    </div>

    <h4>license rel (url)</h4>
    <div>
      The actual link to the rights page should have a rel attribute:
      <ul>
        <li>rel="xhv:license http://www.europeana.eu/schemas/edm/rights"</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <h3>Test</h3>

    <h4>warning</h4>
    <p>
      Keep an eye on the net tab when you open the link - it can time-out contacting scraper.creativecommons.org.
    </p>

    <h4>link</h4>
    <a id="test-link"></a>
    <div>
      Here's the working
      <a href="http://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/mark/1.0/"
         target="_blank">
         test link
      </a>
      to a rights page.  If this is being read from a publicly available server then the above link will contain the text
      "<span class=highlight>Non-binding use guidelines apply to this work.</span>"
      and other data scraped from its referrer, i.e. this page.
    </div>


    <h4>other</h4>
    <div>
       Other metadata used in the old portal included:
       <ul>
         <li>rdfs:seeAlso</li>
         <li>cc:morePermissions</li>
         <li>TODO: find them all</li>
       </ul>
       but that is are not used here.
    </div>

  </body>
